decision tree¶

In [10]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

# Create a decision tree and train
decisionModel = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini', max_leaf_nodes=6)

decisionModel.fit(x_train, y_train)
#only do r2 when target variable is conintuous
print('Rsquared on Training', r2_score(y_train, decisionModel.predict(x_train)))
print(f'Rsquared on Testing, {r2_score(y_test, decisionModel.predict(x_test))}\n')

#do this because target variable is categorical
print('Testing Accuracy is:',decisionModel.score(x_test, y_test))

Rsquared on Training 0.31559265858901664
Rsquared on Testing, 0.3123430465293213

Testing Accuracy is: 0.5814282125361135

In [22]:
df3['color'] = Category20c[len(df3)]

# represent each value as an angle = value / total * 2pi
df3['angle'] = df3['Hospital_code']/df3['Hospital_code'].sum() * 2*pi

p = figure(plot_height=350, title="Length of Stay, Pie Chart", toolbar_location=None,
           tools="hover", tooltips="@real_stay: @Percent%")


p.wedge(x=0, y=1, radius=0.4, 
        
        # use cumsum to cumulatively sum the values for start and end angles
        start_angle=cumsum('angle', include_zero=True), end_angle=cumsum('angle'),
        line_color="white", fill_color='color', legend_field='real_stay', source=df3)

p.axis.axis_label= None
p.axis.visible=False
p.grid.grid_line_color = None

show(p)

about the stacked bar chart¶

- each bucket is broken up into a specified number of patients and each bucket also has a specified amount of data: 
    - 0-4 has 278,051 data points
    - 5-8 has 35,455 data points
    - 9-12 has 3,836 data points
    - 13-16 has 793 data points
    - 17-20 has 155 data points
    - 21-24 has 118 data points
    - 25-28 has 12 data points
    - 29-32 has 18 data points
